{"sequence":17,"timestamp":"2026-04-17T18:02:34.181988391Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-1-24a0ee6b","body":"finding_summary: `run status` now hard-fails on unreadable or corrupt `journal.ndjson`, even for non-milestone projects, because lineage loading was wired through `project::load_project_detail`.\nseverity: high\naffected_files:\n- `src/cli/run.rs`\n- `src/contexts/project_run_record/service.rs`\nevidence:\n- `src/cli/run.rs:2449-2485` makes `load_run_lineage_summary()` call `project::load_project_detail(...)`.\n- `src/cli/run.rs:10766-10770` invokes that helper before the existing snapshot-based status path.\n- `src/contexts/project_run_record/service.rs:1464-1467` shows `show_project()` always reads and parses the journal and propagates failures.\nimpact:\n- Before this patch, `run status` treated journal reads as best-effort (`if let Ok(events) = ...`) and could still report the canonical snapshot from `run.json`.\n- After this patch, any malformed/missing journal, or a transient partial write while a run is active, aborts `run status` before it can print anything. That breaks the additive-output contract and regresses a core monitoring command.\nremediation_hint: Read `project.toml` / `task_source` directly for lineage IDs, then hydrate milestone/bead labels on a best-effort basis. If label lookup fails, fall back to the stored IDs or omit the lineage line instead of routing `run status` through `show_project()`.","dedup_key":"6150d33228bf7bb1e1c204c196ca66c554de6d32b364886b2aa3ef4355f0c6e9","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260417173555","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
